I"…<p>nohup allows is to run a command, close our connection, and still have the command run on the server - very powerful.</p>

<p>Iâ€™ve used this at times I know I have a command that will take a long time to run, but I need to close my laptop / go on lunch / carry on living life.</p>

<p>How to run:</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">nohup </span>COMMAND &amp;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>What is <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&amp;</code> ?- this is to run the command in the background (stops output text appearing in our terminal).</p>

<p>Caveat: If you have trouble with the command not running after disconnecting, you may need to specify a full path. I had this issue with the following MySQL database import, so I used:</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">nohup</span> /usr/bin/mysql ... &amp;
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>instead of</p>
<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="nb">nohup </span>mysql ... &amp;
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Running this you should receive something like the following: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">bash[1] 4587</code> This is our process id - you can use this to monitor the process.</p>

<div class="language-bash highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>ps aux | <span class="nb">grep </span>4587
</code></pre></div></div>
<p>Will give us some details of the current command.</p>

<p>Now you can goto lunch!</p>
:ET